# Prerequisites
*.d

# Compiled Object files
*.slo
*.lo
*.o
*.obj

# Precompiled Headers
*.gch
*.pch

# Compiled Dynamic libraries
*.so
*.dylib
*.dll

# Fortran module files
*.mod
*.smod

# Compiled Static libraries
*.lai
*.la
*.a
*.lib

# Executables
*.exe
*.out
*.app

# CMake build directories (CMakePresets.json's own binaryDir convention)
build/

# clangd / IDE index caches
.cache/
compile_commands.json

# Gradle (testapp/) - caches and build output; none of this is vendored. The wrapper itself
# (gradlew/gradlew.bat/gradle/wrapper/gradle-wrapper.jar) is DELIBERATELY tracked, not ignored -
# see testapp/README.md and ARCHITECTURE.md's CI status table. It used to be listed here (a
# copy-pasted-template mistake - the standard, correct Gradle convention is the opposite: commit
# the wrapper so a fresh checkout builds without a pre-installed Gradle), which is exactly why
# android-build.yml's android-emulator-verify job failed its first real CI run with a plain
# "./gradlew: No such file or directory" - a real gap invisible on this dev machine, which always
# had a real Gradle distribution already installed and never needed ./gradlew to notice it was
# missing.
testapp/.gradle/
testapp/.kotlin/
testapp/**/build/
testapp/**/.cxx/
testapp/.idea/
testapp/local.properties

# Gradle (tools/kotlin-classpath-resolver/) - same shape as testapp/'s own Gradle exclusions above;
# the resolved output directories themselves (a machine-local cache of downloaded jars/AARs) are
# also never committed - see that project's own README for why.
tools/kotlin-classpath-resolver/.gradle/
tools/kotlin-classpath-resolver/local.properties
tools/kotlin-classpath-resolver/resolved-output/

# CMake's own convention: machine-local preset overrides (real NDK/SDK/kotlinc paths for
# whoever's actual dev machine this is) never get committed - see CMakeUserPresets.json itself.
CMakeUserPresets.json
